    "message_1": "One possible question is:\n\nThe transition matrix of a 3-state Markov chain is given by:\n```\nP = [[0.7, 0.2, 0.1],\n     [0.3, 0.4, 0.3],\n     [0.1, 0.3, 0.6]]\n```\nIf the initial state is State 1, what is the probability that the chain will be in State 2 after 4 steps?",
    "message_2": "To find the probability of being in State 2 after 4 steps, we need to raise the transition matrix P to the power of 4 and then multiply it by the initial state vector.\n\nInitial state vector (starting in State 1):\n```\nv = [1, 0, 0]\n```\n\nFirst, let's compute P^4 (P raised to the power of 4):\n\nP^2 = P * P\n```\nP^2 = [[0.7, 0.2, 0.1],   [[0.7, 0.2, 0.1],\n       [0.3, 0.4, 0.3], *   [0.3, 0.4, 0.3],\n       [0.1, 0.3, 0.6]]     [0.1, 0.3, 0.6]]\n\nP^2 = [[0.62, 0.27, 0.11],\n       [0.32, 0.34, 0.34],\n       [0.16, 0.33, 0.51]]\n```\n\nP^4 = P^2 * P^2\n```\nP^4 = [[0.62, 0.27, 0.11],   [[0.62, 0.27, 0.11],\n       [0.32, 0.34, 0.34], *   [0.32, 0.34, 0.34],\n       [0.16, 0.33, 0.51]]     [0.16, 0.33, 0.51]]\n\nP^4 = [[0.5278, 0.2907, 0.1815],\n       [0.3616, 0.3308, 0.3076],\n       [0.2438, 0.3423, 0.4139]]\n```\n\nNow, let's multiply P^4 by the initial state vector v:\n\n```\nP^4 * v = [[0.5278, 0.2907, 0.1815],   [1,\n           [0.3616, 0.3308, 0.3076], *  0,\n           [0.2438, 0.3423, 0.4139]]     0]\n\nP^4 * v = [0.5278, 0.2907, 0.1815]\n```\n\nThe probability of being in State 2 after 4 steps is 0.2907."
